{"questionId":"22202754","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The plane <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>y</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>p</mi><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>q</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>q</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>≠</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence, show that the perpendicular distance between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>11</mn></msqrt></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AB</mi></math> or&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mrow><mi>λ</mi><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>6</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></msqrt></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>11</mn></msqrt></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22202754","referenceCode":"24M.1.AHL.TZ2.11dii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, show that the perpendicular distance between Π1 and Π2 is 11.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.13—Scalar (dot) product","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.14—Vector equation of line","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.17—Vector equations of a plane","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.18—Intersections of lines & planes"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
